definition.value: An (S)-2-trans-abscisic acid D-glucopyranosyl ester derived from beta-D-glucopyranose.
A carboxylic ester that results from the condensation of the carboxylic acid group of (S)-2-trans-abscisic acid with the anomeric hydroxy group of D-glucopyranose.
A triterpenoid saponin that is the 3-O-beta-glucuronide of soyasapogenol B.
A pentacyclic triterpenoid that is oleanane containing a double bond between positions 12 and 13 and substituted by hydroxy groups at the 3beta, 21beta, 22beta and 24-positions.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that results from the removal of a proton from the carboxy group of soyasapogenol B 3-O-beta-glucuronide.
A triterpenoid saponin that is the 3-O-beta-glucuronide of soyasapogenol A.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that results from the removal of a proton from the carboxy group of soyasapogenol A 3-O-beta-glucuronide.

A pentacyclic triterpenoid that is oleanane containing a double bond between positions 12 and 13, and is substituted by hydroxy groups at the 3beta and 24-positions, and by an oxo group at position 22.
A saponin that is the 3-O-beta-glucuronide of soyasapogenol E.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that results from the removal of a proton from the carboxy group of soyasapogenol E 3-O-beta-glucuronide.
A triterpene that is dammarane containing one double bond between the 20 and 21 positions, and another between the 24 and 25 positions.
A monocarboxylic acid anion resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxyl group of indole-3-carboxylic acid.
An acyclic carotene having the structure of psi,psi-carotene shortened by the formal removal of a prenyl group from each end of the molecule.
An apo carotenoid, the dialdehyde formed from 4,4'-diapolycopene.

A branched amino tetrasaccharide comprising N-acetyl-D-glucosamine at the reducing end with a N-acetyl-alpha-D-galactosaminyl-(1->3)-[alpha-L-fucosyl-(1->2)]-beta-D-galactosyl moiety attached at the 3-position.

A triterpenoid that is 4,6,6-trimethylcyclohex-3-en-1-ol which is substituted at position 5 by a (3E,7E,11E)-3,8,12,16-tetramethylheptadeca-3,7,11,15-tetraen-1-yl group, originally isolated from the nonsaponifiable lipids of sasanqua oil (Camellia sasanqua).

A branched amino tetrasaccharide comprising N-acetyl-D-glucosamine at the reducing end with a N-acetyl-alpha-D-galactosaminyl-(1->3)-[alpha-L-fucosyl-(1->2)]-beta-D-galactosyl moiety attached at the 4-position.
An alpha-D-GalpNAc-(1->3)-[alpha-L-Fucp-(1->2)]-beta-D-Galp-(1->3)-D-GalpNAc having alpha-configuration at the reducing end anomeric centre.
A pentacyclic triterpenoid that is oleanane substituted by a hydroxy group at the 3beta-position and with a double bond between positioins 18 and 19.
A tetracyclic triterpenoid that is 4,9-cyclo-9,10-secocholesta-5,24-diene substituted by methyl groups at the 9beta, 10, and 14 positions, and by a hydroxy group at position 1.
A 3beta-hydroxy steroid having an ent-dammarane skeleton with a double bond at C-24 and a Z-double bond at C-17(20).
A pentacyclic triterpenoid that is oleanane substituted by hydroxy groups at the 3beta and 22beta positions and containing a double bond between positions 12 and 13.
A pentacyclic triterpenoid that is oleanane which is substituted by hydroxy groups at the 3beta and 24 positions, and which has a double bond between positions 12 and 13.
A steroid C-21 acid having a 29-nordammarane skeleton substituted with an acetoxy group at C-16 and oxo groups at C-3 and -7, with double bonds at C-1, -17(20) and -24.
The steroid acid anion formed by loss of a proton from the carboxy group of helvolic acid; major microspecies at pH 7.3.
An oxopurine that is 3,7-dihydro-purin-2-one in which the hydrogen at position 6 is substituted by an amino group.
An acyclic carotene having the structure 7',8'-dihydro-psi,psi-carotene with cis-double bonds at C-7, C-9 and C-9'.
A serine derivative that is L-serine having a 3-O-beta-D-galactosyl-N-acetyl-alpha-D-galactosaminyl moiety attached to the side-chain oxygen.

An amino acid zwitterion that is the zwitterionic form of O-(3-O-beta-D-galactosyl-N-acetyl-alpha-D-galactosaminyl)-L-serine arising from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
An acyclic psi,psi-carotene having cis double bonds at C-7, -7', -9 and -9'.
A linear amino tetrasaccharide consisting of alpha-fucosyl, beta-galactosyl, beta-glucosaminyl and beta-galactose units connected via sequential (1->2)-, (1->3)- and (1->3)-linkages.

A linear amino pentasaccharide consisting of alpha-fucosyl, beta-galactosyl, beta-glucosaminyl,  beta-galactosyl and glucose units connected via sequential (1->2)-, (1->4)-, (1->3)- and (1->4)-linkages.

A linear amino tetrasaccharide consisting of alpha-fucosyl, beta-galactosyl, beta-glucosaminyl, beta-galactosyl and glucose units connected via sequential (1->2)-, (1->3)-, (1->4)- and (1->4)-linkages.
An acyclic carotene having the structure of lycopene with two hydrogen atoms abstracted from the C(3)-C(4) bond to form an extra trans double bond.
A seven-membered glucosamine oligosaccharide made up from one glucose, one fucose, two glucosamine and three galactose units in a linear sequence, linked as shown.
A glycosylrhamnose that is 4-deoxy-beta-L-threo-hex-4-enopyranuronose joined by a (1->2)-glycosidic link to alpha-L-rhamnopyranose.
A linear amino hexasaccharide made up from one glucosamine, one glucose, one fucose and three galactose residues, linked as shown.
A hexuronate that results from the removal of a proton from the carboxy group of 2-O-(4-deoxy-beta-L-threo-hex-4-enopyranuronosyl)-alpha-L-rhamnopyranose.
A hexuronic acid that is 3,4-dihydro-2H-pyran-6-carboxylic acid substituted by a hydroxy group at each of the positions 2, 3, and 4 (the 2S,3R,4S-diastereoisomer).
The carotenone that is the 2-oxo derivative of (3E)-1-methoxy-3,4-didehydro-1,2,7',8'-tetrahydro-psi,psi-carotene.
A carotenol having the structure of rhodopin with two hydrogen atoms abstracted from the C(3)-C(4) bond to form an extra trans double bond.
A hexuronate that results from the removal of a proton from the carboxy group of 4-deoxy-beta-L-threo-hex-4-enopyranuronic acid.
A branched ten-membered glucosamine oligosaccharide consisting of two fucose, three glucosamine, one glucose (at the reducing end) and four galactose units, linked as shown.
A branched eight-membered glucosamine oligosaccharide consisting of two fucose, two glucosamine, one glucose (at the reducing end) and three galactose units, linked as shown.
An alpha-D-GalpNAc-(1->3)-[alpha-L-Fucp-(1->2)]-beta-D-Galp-(1->3)-D-GlcpNAc having beta-configuration at the reducing end anomeric centre.

A branched amino tetrasaccharide comprising N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine at the reducing end with a N-acetyl-alpha-D-galactosaminyl-(1->3)-[alpha-L-fucosyl-(1->2)]-beta-D-galactosyl moiety attached at the 4-position.
A (3'->5')-dinucleotide consisting of 2'-deoxyguanosine having a 2'-deoxycytidylyl-3-phospho moiety attached at the 5-position.

A molecular messenger in which the molecule is specifically involved in transmitting information between cells. Such molecules are released from the cell sending the signal, cross over the gap between cells by diffusion, and interact with specific receptors in another cell, triggering a response in that cell by activating a series of enzyme controlled reactions which lead to changes inside the cell.

An alpha-L-rhamnoside consisting of D-glucitol having an alpha-L-Rhap-(1->2)-[alpha-L-Rhap-(1->2)-alpha-D-Galp-(1->3)-beta-D-GlcpNAc-(1->4)]-alpha-L-Rhap-(1->2)-alpha-L-Rhap moiety attached at the 1-position and an alpha-L-Rhap residue at the 3-position.
